        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear Waterhouse</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am so determined to make you a geologist, that I have taken the liberty of sending you a copy of Lyell,<ref target="#foot.f1"/> by which means I obtain full right to mal-treat &amp; abuse you till you have read it.</p>
<p>Ever yours | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The reference is either to Lyell’s <hi rend="italic">Elements</hi>, which was published in August 1838 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-424.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Charles Lyell, 9 August [1838]</ref>), or to the sixth edition of the <hi rend="italic">Principles</hi>, published in 1840.</note>
        </div>        
            
